title: For Sale:  Mint Smith & Wesson .357 Mag/.38 Special Model 60-9 2" Revolver
postcontent:
For sale is a mint condition (less than 10 rounds through the pipe) Smith & Wesson 5-shot model 60-9 "pre-agreement" revolver.  For those who don't know, "pre-agreement" means this revolver has no lock for the cylinder as newer Smith & Wesson's do, circa 1994 and on.   This beauty accepts either .357 Magnum or .38 Special (regular and +P), features super rosewood grips by Altamont, a full velvet hone finish by Magnaport, a jeweled and polished trigger and hammer also by Magnaport, polished flute cylinders, ejection rod, inverted muzzle crown and dual barrel ports, all done by Magnaport as well.  It also comes with a new, buttery soft, custom full-grain Italian leather holster by Blackhawk.  

I inherited this revolver in it's current condition, it was purchased new and exactly 10 rounds total have been fired through it (by myself), post customization by Magnaport, just to make sure none of the finish work obstructed any function.  It fires perfectly and more than accurately, with greatly reduced recoil and muzzle flip due to the dual ports on the barrel.  This is a perfect sidearm for CCW, home defense, or just about any other application a person can need.  

The only reason I'm selling is to re-invest in a platinum Sig Sauer 1911 to match the other one that I already own.  This revolver will ship in it's own hard-sided case, complete with holster, original grips, original paperwork and Magnaport custom paperwork (totaling $450) and a new cleaning kit with Ballistol cleaning wipes.  I'm a firearm collector/enthusiast, I know what I'm talking about and don't false advertise.  If you have any questions, feel more than free to email me, and I will reply promptly.  

I will consider trades.  I'm mostly interested in Sig Sauer or Kimber full-size 1911's at the moment, have a few and absolutely love them.  I'll consider decent offers as well, let's talk!  If you're looking for a nice piece for your significant other, guarantee she'll like this.

Lake City/Federal 5.56 ammo is the best 5.56 military ammo manufactured. This is XM855 specification ammo with the SS109 penetrator bullet. The SS109 is a 62 grain projectile with a lead core and a steel penetrator designed for combat use.

XM855 ammo features a 62 grain, copper jacketed, lead core, steel tip bullet. It is not armor piercing ammunition, but the steel tip does allow it to penetrate farther than other types of ammo. This bullet will attract a magnet because of the steel in the tip, and some ranges will not allow you to use it because of this. However, it will not damage the barrel of your rifle, because the steel is entirely covered by a layer of copper.

The ammunition itself is extremely high quality, and has features not seen on other ammunition of this type. This ammo has a crimped primer, reducing the chances of a blown primer stopping a semi-automatic, or automatic rifle from functioning. It also has a lacquer primer sealant and a case mouth sealant, to prevent the internal components from being compromised by moisture intrusion.

Federal offers a weather resistant ammo can containing 420 rounds of this ammunition. Composed of 14 30-round boxes containing three stripper clips of 10 rounds each, this product is ideal for those looking to store ammo long term, but who also want to be able to access and load it quickly

Stainless AMT Backup 9mm $450
This is the full 9mm, not the short (.380)  it's an AMT Backup, DAO in 9mm.  All stainless, I believe there's not a bit of plastic or rubber on it - even the grips are fiberglass. But I did put on a houge rubber grip, visible in the photos.  It's about as small as you can find in a 9mm, even some of todays compacts are bigger than this bad boy.  It weighs a ton, right about 21 ounces with a full mag (6 rounds).  
It's Double Action Only - hammer fired, which means it's got a trigger pull that's probably heaver than even the New York Glocks  - I believe the specs say this is 14 oz. I know it takes a very deliberate pull,  no hair triggers ere folks.  It's got all the original factory paperwork and box,  a spare mag, a very nice Don Hume molded IWB and a generic leather mag carrier.  And parts are still available if you should ever need them (HI-Standard bought out AMT, and still has a lot of stuff for these)

Like all brands, you'll find both good and bad reviews on the web, and this one is no different.  Personally I think the bad reviews are all crap. This thing is as crisp and clean as the day it was made, the machine work on it is top quality, and I didn't have one hiccup in the hundred rounds I've put through it.  It feeds everything I've put in it with no issues, it shoots straight - every time,   there's no safties or even a hold-open so it's got very very few moving parts.

If it were a couple ounces lighter I might keep it,  but I went for an ankle carry and this is just too heavy for wear like that.    It does fit great at the 4:00 position, but at 6 rounds I'm reluctant to make it my primary.
